{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Server*. Using *Confluence Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFCLOUD-2640].
  {panel}

It is essential that we identify what has been going wrong with the 10g drivers and provide a satisfactory workaround.

Some imports work (demonstration space) while others do not (large imports from recent history).

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Server*. Using *Confluence Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFCLOUD-2618].
  {panel}

When importing an archive we sometimes encounter a stack-trace about a missing attachment, etc.. (I'll attach evidence).

We should report the associated pages so these attachments can be tracked down.

Exception messages, in general, should be useful towards hunting down the problem and improving the state of data in a problematic archive.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Server*. Using *Confluence Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFCLOUD-2611].
  {panel}

When I saw the "Import pages from disk" action, I thought of how this might make it easier for us to import information into Confluence.  However, most of the directories I could think of have a mix of documents, presentations, PDFs, or text files. Importing a directory with a mix of these is not useful.  It would be great if the import could be made more intelligent by creating pages for certain extensions (txt) and allowing other extensions (doc, pdf, prs, xls, ...) to be imported as attachments.  What page would the attachments belong to?  Perhaps all on the same page named after the directory it came from? Perhaps a user specified page? Perhaps each attachment is its own page with the name taken from the file like the current support?  The last option is probably the most flexible and easier to start with.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Server*. Using *Confluence Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFCLOUD-2610].
  {panel}

Need to control how often POP account is polled similar to support in JIRA to make sure we are not overloading POP server.  How often is it done now?

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Server*. Using *Confluence Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFCLOUD-2589].
  {panel}

The JUnit Report macro can only build a report based on one file. 

An option should exist for specifying multiple files and building one report representing all of them.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Server*. Using *Confluence Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFCLOUD-2587].
  {panel}

Comments on pages should be ordered according to administrator's preference - the most recent comment can appear at the top or the bottom of the list.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Server*. Using *Confluence Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFCLOUD-2584].
  {panel}

It would be nice to be able to caption images in some way.  Currently, if you display and center an image, the only way I can think to get a caption-like thing on it is to use a user macro to wrap the caption in, e.g., <span class="caption">...</span> or something similar, but this disallows Confluence markup.

Maybe just 
{noformat}
!image.ext|caption=<markup>! 
{noformat}
?

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Server*. Using *Confluence Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFCLOUD-2579].
  {panel}

Themes (decorators, CSS, etc..) could be associated with users or groups of them. This would allow dramatically different views of content in Confluence.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Server*. Using *Confluence Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFCLOUD-2562].
  {panel}

It should be much easier to create a link to a mail message. Currently you have to know the "internal database ID" to link a mail. This is very unhandy. A link-by-subject would be much better.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
